Exercise 1: Exploratory Data Analysis

  1. Visualize the distribution of score in the dataframe evals.
# add code here
ggplot(data = evals, aes(x = score)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1, fill = "navyblue", color = "white") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Course Evaluation Scores", x = "Score", y = "Count")

The distribution is left-skewed, that means most scores are high students tend to rate professors favorably. This is expected because students often rate courses positively unless something went very wrong.

  1. Visualize and describe the relationship between score and bty_avg using geom_point() to represent the data.
# add code here
ggplot(evals, aes(x = bty_avg, y = score)) +
  geom_point(width = 0.2, height = 0.2, alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(title = "Score vs. Beauty Average (Point)", x = "Average Beauty Rating", y = "Course Score")

Exercise 2: Simple Linear regression with a numerical predictor

  1. Fit a linear model called score_bty_fit to predict average professor evaluation score from average beauty rating (bty_avg). Print the regression output using tidy().
# remove eval = FALSE from the code chunk options after filling in the blanks
score_bty_fit <- linear_reg() %>%
  set_engine("lm") %>%
  fit(score ~ bty_avg, data = evals)
# remove eval = FALSE from the code chunk options after filling in the blanks
tidy(score_bty_fit)

Add your linear model here. Dont worry too much about notation, you can use things like score-hat.

  1. Plot the data again using geom_jitter(), and add the regression line.
# add your plot here. Hint, you can add the regression line using geom_smooth()
ggplot(evals, aes(x = bty_avg, y = score)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, height = 0.2, alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Regression Line for Score vs. Beauty Rating")
  1. Interpret the slope of the linear model in context of the data.

Slope (0.066): For each 1-point increase in beauty rating, predicted course score increases by 0.066 points. Intercept (3.88): Predicted score when beauty rating = 0.

  1. Interpret the intercept of the linear model in context of the data. Comment on whether or not the intercept makes sense in this context.

Add your interpretation here

  1. Determine the \(R^2\) of the model and interpret it in the context of the data.
# remove eval = FALSE from the code chunk options after filling in the blanks
glance(score_bty_fit)$r.squared

Beauty explains about 3.5% of the variability in course scores.

  1. Make a plot of residuals vs.predicted values for the model above.
# remove eval = FALSE from the code chunk options after filling in the blanks
score_bty_aug <- augment(score_bty_fit$fit)
ggplot(score_bty_aug, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.05, height = 0.05, alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(title = "Residuals vs Fitted Values", x = "Predicted Score", y = "Residuals")
